summary.text:
...use all your senses...
Ever heard of a piping plover?

Tiny bird. Almost blends into the sand.
But watch it for a second — and you’ll see what working smart really looks like.
The piping plover survives by doing one thing incredibly well:
It uses all its senses.
It doesn’t charge blindly.
It listens. Watches. Feels. Adjusts.
And only moves when the time is right.
Smart, not loud.
Present, not frantic.
Precise, not busy.
We could learn a lot from that.
Because most of us are doing too much —
but feeling very little.

This is for you:

1 | Work in “Pulse Sprints” — not marathons
How: Focus fully for 25–40 mins, then step away. No scrolling, just step out. Breathe. Move. Look around.
Why: Your brain processes ideas in the gaps. Pushing longer often gives you less.

2 | Do regular “gut checks” instead of long reviews
How: Once a week, ask: “What feels off?” Not “what’s wrong” — just what feels off.
Why: Your gut often knows before your mind catches up. This helps you course-correct early.

3 | Observe before you act 
How: Don’t respond to every notification or problem right away. Pause. Zoom out.
Why: The best responses come after watching, not reacting. Stillness is a strategy.

The piping plover is a rolemodel.
Because it pays attention. And uses all its senses.
Maybe that’s what we need more of.

Keep growing,
Carina Hellmich

summary.text:
A grown woman who can't spell or use grammar correctly 🥴 dyslexia has always been the bane of my corporate career.

I was diagnosed with dyslexia at 30 🫤

Writing emails
Board papers 
Insight papers
Preparing decks 
Responding to feedback 
Writing performance reviews 
Writing to clients 

Before my diagnosis, I was so ashamed and embarrassed… I feared I was constantly being judged, assessed and criticised for simple spelling mistakes, grammatical errors and minor typos 😮‍💨

I’ve spent my entire career navigating boardrooms, leading teams, and driving complex strategies — all while managing the realities of being neurodiverse. 

As someone with dyslexia, I’ve often questioned who gets to say what professionalism means! 🤷🏾‍♀️

We’ve been taught that “professionalism” looks like perfection. Impeccable spelling. Immaculate slides. Instant memory recall. A polished, error-free presentity 🥴

But when you have dyslexia or ADHD, your brilliance often lives beyond those norms — in ideas, innovation, intuition, solutions and likeability. Yet, I have spent so much energy masking, compensating, and striving to fit a mould never built for us.

Most organisations aren’t yet equipped to support neurodivergent leaders. This is not because they don’t care—it's because they haven’t truly understood the mechanism to unlock our superpowers!

It isn't with kindness but with resources, compassion and forgiveness:

1. Resources
Dyslexia-friendly software, speech-to-text tools, and mind—mapping platforms aren’t perks. They are productivity enablers. Ultimately, supporting neurodiversity is not cheap—it can't be done by goodwill! It needs a budget, focus and investment, leaders need to be trained, and difference needs to be celebrated. 

2. Compassionate Leadership
We need leaders who lead with care, who ask, not assume, and who create space for vulnerability without penalty. Compassion isn’t soft—it’s strategic. As a leader, how can you help? I've had leaders offer to check my work, send me templates, and correct me with kindness. 

3. A Culture of forgiveness
Mistakes should be part of learning, not a career-limiting move. For neurodiverse professionals, the fear of making mistakes can be paralysing. Mistakes are seen as tardiness, unprofessional and incompetent. What if we created a culture where mistakes are met with curiosity, not criticism? Where they are corrected, and potential is elevated. 

Just yesterday, after I shared a post on LinkedIn, a friend privately messaged me to let me know I had a spelling mistake. Years ago, I would have been overcome with embarrassment and shame. But over the years, I’ve deeply appreciated the kindness of others — those who offer support, with no judgment. 

Those small acts of grace make a big difference.

How many organisations have ‘Grace’ as a value? 

When kindness, compassion, grace and empathy become part of the culture, people feel safe showing up as they are and delivering their best work.

Be kind 🙂 its free

Dear LinkedIners! 

For the tea drinkers, let’s bring out the camomile shall we??  While we sip, allow me to answer this powerful question that came from a member of my community here on LinkedIn.  

“Hello Anita. I find myself always so lost in large gatherings like conferences. I feel invisible. I know you've always been this bold and outspoken? How did you become this person? Especially in spaces that can be so intimidating?”

Now. I want to start by saying this: I wasn’t always this way. In fact, I used to go to summits and conferences as an entrepreneur desperate to connect. I came prepared—business cards, elevator pitch, polished LinkedIn. But I’d leave disappointed, discouraged… and feeling invisible.

The rooms were full of big names, big voices, big energy. And me? Every time I tried to approach someone I admired, their PA or security would whisk them away. I felt like I didn’t matter.

And that’s when I learned something intense that confirms your question : YOU CAN BE INVISIBLE IN PLAIN SIGHT. Not because people can’t see you—but because they can’t feel you.

Then one day, everything changed. A keynote speaker made a comment that struck a nerve. His words moved something in me. So when he ended his talk, I raised my hand.

He looked surprised. “Oh, I didn’t know I was taking questions.”

My heart was racing. My knees were shaking. But I smiled, grabbing the mic and said, “I know, Your Excellency. But this room is full of a constituency that’s truly only here for you. One quick question, sir?”

That moment shifted everything. The room applauded my powerful question, inspiring other questions. 

And for the very first time, a high-level speaker came to me and asked, “What’s your name?”
That day, I discovered what I now know to be the intentionality of being seen and heard! 

So no, I wasn’t always bold. I wasn’t always outspoken. But I became this version of myself by refusing to let fear sit in the driver’s seat.

Here are my Top 5 ways to speak in a room that scared me—especially when I felt small, lost, or invisible:

1. Breathe before you speak. Let calmness steady you.
2. Own one insight. You don’t need to impress—just express something real.
3. Find one friendly face. Anchor your voice in connection.
4. Ask a question if you can’t offer a comment. Engagement is presence.
5. Speak like someone needs to hear you. Because someone always does.

I know you feel lost and invisible—let me tell you something I wish someone had told me:

YOU HAVE A VOICE. USE IT ….YOUR WAY!! 

Whether you speak, sign, write, or gesture—you deserve to be heard. Even if it trembles, especially when it does—let people experience you.

Because communication, in any form, is how the world begins to experience you!

In simple terms SQL (Structured Query Language) is a standard programming language used to manage and manipulate relational databases. 

It enables users to create, retrieve, update, and delete data from databases. 
SQL is widely used in various applications, from small-scale software to large enterprise-level systems. 

Common SQL operations include querying data using SELECT, inserting data with INSERT, updating records with UPDATE, and deleting records with DELETE. 

It also supports database management features like defining tables, constraints, and handling transactions.

🔰 SQL Interview Preparation Process:

1. Master the Basics: Understand core SQL concepts such as SELECT statements, joins (INNER, LEFT, RIGHT, FULL OUTER), filtering with WHERE, GROUP BY, and aggregation functions (COUNT, SUM, AVG).

2. Practice Advanced Queries: Dive into complex topics like subqueries, window functions, Common Table Expressions (CTEs), indexing, and query optimization techniques.

3. Hands-on Practice: Work with real databases and platforms like LeetCode or HackerRank or NamasteSQL to solve SQL problems, focusing on performance and optimization.

4. Understand Database Design: Be prepared to discuss normalization, relationships (one-to-one, one-to-many), keys (primary, foreign), and ACID properties.

5. Review SQL Use Cases: Study how SQL is used in data analysis, reporting, and interacting with backend systems.

6. Mock Interviews: Practice solving SQL problems under time constraints and explaining your thought process clearly.

summary.text:
The most impactful strategies for LinkedIn growth are selfish and don't actually reward good content. Here's what I do instead.

𝗦𝗼𝗰𝗶𝗮𝗹 𝗴𝗿𝗼𝘄𝘁𝗵 𝗮𝘁 𝗮𝗹𝗹 𝗰𝗼𝘀𝘁

I've written often about how pods allow some to game LinkedIn using automated likes and comments, so I shall not belabour the point today.

(Read: https://lnkd.in/gyqPhgS9)

There are other methods that work really well, too, but which don't benefit readers.

🔸𝗔𝗜-𝗽𝗼𝘄𝗲𝗿𝗲𝗱 𝗰𝗼𝗺𝗺𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴: It makes sense that LinkedIn rewards engagements. Churn out 100 comments a day with AI and watch impressions soar. But what's the value of another bland summary with zero insight?

🔸𝗥𝗲𝘂𝘀𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝘀𝗮𝗺𝗲 𝗽𝗼𝘀𝘁: Since LinkedIn only shows your post to a fraction of connections, why not just reuse them using AI? The result? A never-ending scroll of the same recycled thoughts.

🔸𝗣𝗹𝗮𝗴𝗶𝗮𝗿𝗶𝘀𝗶𝗻𝗴: Creating content is tough, so why not just copy from trending posts out there? Take either the entire post or use large swathes with a new line or two. Then pretend everything is yours.

To be clear, I don't see my circle of friends doing the above. But it's out there, giving those who care less about quality content outsized metrics.

𝗔 𝗯𝗲𝘁𝘁𝗲𝗿 𝘄𝗮𝘆

I think we should respect the time of readers. That's why I ignore impressions and focus on quality content that adds value.

Here are the 3 principles that guide my content here.

𝟭/ 𝗪𝗿𝗶𝘁𝗲 𝘂𝗻𝗶𝗾𝘂𝗲 𝗰𝗼𝗻𝘁𝗲𝗻𝘁

When I started writing daily two years ago, I decided I'd only share stuff that can't be found elsewhere. For every post, I add in my:

- Insights.
- Opinions.
- Learnings.

And it's written in my voice - which means you'll look weird trying to pass it off as your own.

𝟮/ 𝗟𝗶𝗻𝗸 𝘁𝗼 𝗼𝗹𝗱𝗲𝗿 𝗽𝗼𝘀𝘁𝘀

Since every post is unique, it made sense to link to them when relevant. I know it works because I still get the occasional "likes" to posts from months and months ago.

And oh, I've also put all my posts on a standalone blog you can easily reference at www.techstories.co. Check it out if you've not done so.

𝟯/ 𝗔𝘁𝘁𝗿𝗶𝗯𝘂𝘁𝗲, 𝗻𝗼𝘁 𝗽𝗹𝗮𝗴𝗶𝗮𝗿𝗶𝘀𝗲 

I'm only human and don't know everything. But when I rely on insights from other sources, I make it a point to attribute it to them. This includes every photo that I use, going back two years now.

𝗞𝗲𝗲𝗽 𝗴𝗼𝗶𝗻𝗴

What keeps me going isn't impressions (I stopped looking years ago) or even engagements. 

It's those DMs from professionals who are experts in their various fields. Or the rich comments that they make the effort to leave. That's the ultimate validation to me.

What about you? What keeps you going?
 
📆 𝗚𝗲𝘁 𝗺𝘆 𝗰𝗼𝗻𝘁𝗲𝗻𝘁

Don't be limited by what LinkedIn shows you. Get my weekly digest via email: www.techstories.co/updates

My name is Paul Mah and I explore tech developments with bite-sized reports in #EverydayTechStories

The biggest mistake people make on LinkedIn is quitting too early.

Most users follow this pattern...

→ Post content for just one month
→ Get minimal engagement
→ Give up completely

But success doesn't happen overnight.

Let me share my journey:

Month 1: Zero likes, zero traction
Month 3: 5-10 likes per post
Month 6: 50-100 likes consistently
Month 9: 300-500 likes regularly

Then it happened:

1,000+ likes, 100,000 impressions on one LinkedIn post.

The secret?

I kept showing up daily.

Here's what you actually need to succeed:

1. Define who you want to help and how
2. Solve a clear problem
3. Share your expertise

Remember: It's not about reaching everyone.

It's about reaching the right people who need your solution.

Start building your presence before everyone else catches up.

P.S. How long have you been posting on LinkedIn?
